{"message": "No, I don't think that's more accurate. I said what I meant.

The research on remote work is pretty clear — productivity increases or stays the same, employee satisfaction goes up, and people get hours of their lives back from commuting. The push to force people back into offices overwhelmingly comes from management cultures uncomfortable with autonomy, or from companies trying to justify expensive real estate.

I'm not going to pretend both sides are equally valid when the evidence leans heavily in one direction. That's not balance — it's false equivalence."}
